<i>Burning in my heart ♪</i>

29:33.083 --> 29:38.125
<i>♪ I can't keep from crying</i>
<i>It's tearing me apart ♪</i>

29:41.083 --> 29:45.708
<i>♪ Ooh, heat wave ♪</i>

29:46.833 --> 29:51.583
<i>♪ Ooh, heat wave ♪</i>

29:54.791 --> 29:56.791
-God damn it, Hank!
-Why would you--

30:03.500 --> 30:06.583
I thought… I'm…
You said that you weren't coming.

30:06.666 --> 30:08.291
Well, I'm sorry.

30:10.083 --> 30:12.458
Well, we were just acting silly.

30:13.958 --> 30:16.458
When I called,
I was at a phone booth around the corner.

30:16.541 --> 30:18.083
My dinner party isn't far from here.

30:18.166 --> 30:21.041
Emory was showing us this silly dance.

30:21.125 --> 30:23.250
I walked past,
and your downstairs door was open.

30:23.333 --> 30:24.375
This is Emory.

30:27.750 --> 30:29.125
Everybody, this is Alan McCarthy.

30:29.208 --> 30:34.166
Alan, counterclockwise, we have
Larry, Bernard, Donald, Emory and Hank.

30:34.250 --> 30:35.500
-Nice to meet you.
-Hi.

30:35.583 --> 30:38.583
-Would you like a drink?
-Thanks, no. I-I can't stay long.

30:38.666 --> 30:41.250
You're here now, so stay.
What would you like?

30:41.333 --> 30:42.666
-Scotch, please.
-Scotch.

30:42.750 --> 30:44.583
-I'll get it.
- Thank you.

30:49.875 --> 30:52.375
-Guess I'm the only beer drinker.

30:53.041 --> 30:54.875
Whose, uh, birthday is it?

30:54.958 --> 30:56.750
-Harold's.
- Harold?

30:56.833 --> 30:59.583
- He's not here yet.
-She's never been on time in her li--

31:01.916 --> 31:05.041
He's… never been on time in his life.

31:05.125 --> 31:09.875
Hank, Alan is from Washington.
We went to college together, Georgetown.

31:09.958 --> 31:10.958
-Ah.
-Yeah.

31:13.125 --> 31:14.750
Well, isn't that fascinating?

31:14.833 --> 31:17.416
If that's too strong,
I'll put some water in it for you.

31:18.958 --> 31:20.750
It's fine, thanks. Fine.

31:22.875 --> 31:25.666
-You in the government, Alan?
-No, I'm a lawyer.

31:25.750 --> 31:27.500
-What do you do?
-I teach school.

31:27.583 --> 31:30.416
Oh. Would have taken you
for an athlete of some sort.

31:33.458 --> 31:35.250
You look like you might play sports.

31:35.333 --> 31:39.000
Well, I'm no professional, but I was
on the basketball team in college.

31:39.083 --> 31:41.166
-Played quite a bit of tennis.
-I play tennis, too.

31:41.250 --> 31:43.291
-Great game. It is, yeah.
- Yeah, great.

31:45.166 --> 31:46.625
-What do you teach?
-Math.

31:46.708 --> 31:47.958
-Math?
-Yeah.

31:48.541 --> 31:49.375
Math.

31:51.291 --> 31:55.041
Kind of makes you want to rush out
and buy a slide rule, doesn't it?

31:56.041 --> 31:57.791
Emory, I need help in the kitchen.

31:57.875 --> 32:00.041
-You're elected. Come on.
-I'm always elected.

32:00.125 --> 32:02.958
-You're a natural-born domestic.
-Said the African queen!

32:03.041 --> 32:05.291
You come, too. Fan me
while I make the salad dressing.

32:05.375 --> 32:07.125
- This way, Emory.

32:11.750 --> 32:12.750
Why don't we all sit down?

32:12.833 --> 32:13.916
-Sure.
-Yeah.

32:24.166 --> 32:26.583
I feel terrible
barging in on you fellas this way.

32:26.666 --> 32:27.541
Ah, that's okay.

32:27.625 --> 32:30.791
- How've you been?
-Fine, thanks. And you?

32:33.375 --> 32:34.416
You married?

32:35.750 --> 32:37.500
-What?
-I see you're married.

32:37.583 --> 32:38.750
Oh.

32:38.833 --> 32:42.333
Yes, Hank is married.
Donald, cope with some ice.

32:44.541 --> 32:46.458
-Do you have any kids?
-Yes, two.

32:46.541 --> 32:47.916
A boy, nine. A girl, seven.

32:48.500 --> 32:51.708
You should see my boy play tennis.
Really puts his dad to shame.

32:51.791 --> 32:53.958
-I have two kids, too. Both girls.
- Great.

32:54.708 --> 32:57.458
-How are the girls, Alan?
-Oh, just sensational.

32:57.541 --> 32:59.708
-Yeah?
-They're something, those kids.

32:59.791 --> 33:01.750
God, I'm-I'm nuts about them.

33:03.125 --> 33:04.916
-How long you been married?
- Nine years.

33:05.000 --> 33:06.375
Ah!

33:06.458 --> 33:08.625
-Can you believe it, Mickey?
-No.

33:09.208 --> 33:11.708
Mickey used to go with my wife
when we were all in school.

33:11.791 --> 33:13.416
-Can you believe that?

33:13.500 --> 33:16.125
Oh, Lord. Sorry.

33:21.208 --> 33:22.500
You live in the city?

33:23.250 --> 33:26.000
Yes, we do.

33:30.958 --> 33:31.958
Oh!

33:32.458 --> 33:34.625
I'm in
the process of getting a divorce.

33:35.125 --> 33:38.666
-Larry and I are roommates at the moment.
-Yes, they're roommates.

33:39.958 --> 33:42.208
Oh, I'm very sorry. I mean--

33:42.291 --> 33:43.916
-No, I understand.
- Mmm.

33:48.041 --> 33:50.791
-I think I'd like another.
-Of course. I'm so sorry.

33:55.125 --> 33:56.291
Can I help you, Alan?

33:56.958 --> 33:58.041
Uh…

33:59.583 --> 34:01.166
Can't seem to find the scotch.

34:02.000 --> 34:03.166
It's in your hand.

34:03.250 --> 34:04.875
-Oh.

34:04.958 --> 34:06.208
Of course. How stupid of me.

34:06.291 --> 34:08.791
-Why don't you let me do that for you?
-Thank you.

34:08.875 --> 34:12.833
-Where the hell could Harold be?
-Oh, he's always late.

34:12.916 --> 34:15.291
You know how neurotic
he can be about going out in public.

34:15.375 --> 34:16.791
Takes him hours to get ready.

34:16.875 --> 34:18.708
-Why is that?
-Why is what?

34:18.791 --> 34:21.958
Why does it take Harold hours
to get ready before he can go out?

34:22.750 --> 34:24.541
Because she's a sick lady. That's why.

34:24.625 --> 34:26.708
Alan, why don't we go upstairs and talk?

34:26.791 --> 34:28.583
I'm just gonna finish this and go.

34:28.666 --> 34:30.833
Come on. You can bring your drink.

34:31.750 --> 34:33.791
-I-I finished it.
- Here.

34:40.291 --> 34:43.583
-Excuse me. We'll be down in a minute.
-Oh, he'll still be here.

34:44.875 --> 34:46.625
-Come on. This way, Alan.
-Sure.

34:54.375 --> 34:55.583
What was that supposed to mean?

34:55.666 --> 34:57.791
-What was what supposed to mean?
-You know.

34:58.875 --> 35:00.375
-Do you want another beer?
-No.

35:02.208 --> 35:03.625
You're jealous, aren't you?

35:03.708 --> 35:05.833
-I'm Larry.

35:06.958 --> 35:08.166
You're jealous.

35:10.375 --> 35:12.500
So, Donald, where have you been
hanging out these days?

35:12.583 --> 35:14.333
I haven't seen you in a long time.

35:19.666 --> 35:21.125
- Alan…

35:23.291 --> 35:26.833
I want to try to explain
something about this evening.

35:26.916 --> 35:29.291
What's to explain? Sometimes you just…

35:29.375 --> 35:31.583
can't invite everybody
to every party, and…

35:32.166 --> 35:34.458
Some people take it personally,
but not me.

35:34.541 --> 35:36.791
I should apologize for inviting myself.

35:36.875 --> 35:38.958
That is not exactly what I meant.

35:39.666 --> 35:42.250
Your friends seem like awfully nice guys.

35:43.041 --> 35:44.958
That Hank is a very attractive fellow.

35:45.541 --> 35:46.666
Yes, he is.

35:47.500 --> 35:50.083
-What's his roommate's name?
-Uh, Larry.

35:50.166 --> 35:51.000
What does he do?

35:52.166 --> 35:53.708
He's a commercial artist.

35:53.791 --> 35:56.291
I liked Donald, too.

35:59.583 --> 36:01.916
The only one
I didn't care for too much was…

36:02.625 --> 36:04.041
What's his name? Emory?

36:04.125 --> 36:05.916
Yes, Emory.

36:06.541 --> 36:09.125
Just can't stand that kind of talk.
It grates on me.

36:13.541 --> 36:15.333
What kind of talk, Alan?

36:15.416 --> 36:19.458
Oh, you know, his…
brand of humor, I guess.

36:19.541 --> 36:22.250
He can be really quite funny sometimes.

36:22.333 --> 36:25.291
I suppose, if you find
that sort of thing amusing. He just…

36:26.083 --> 36:28.458
seems like such a goddamn little pansy.

36:31.583 --> 36:34.333
I'm sorry I said that.
I didn't mean to say that. That's…

36:35.541 --> 36:38.083
such an awful thing
to say about anyone.

36:38.958 --> 36:40.750
But you know what I mean, Michael.

36:41.458 --> 36:43.375
You have to admit he is effeminate.

36:45.000 --> 36:47.000
-He is a bit.
-A bit?

36:48.125 --> 36:50.083
He's like a butterfly in heat.

36:51.416 --> 36:54.083
There's no wonder
he was teaching you all to dance.

36:54.875 --> 36:57.166
He probably wanted to dance with you.

37:01.333 --> 37:03.416
Oh, come on, man. You know me.

37:04.625 --> 37:08.458
You know how I feel.
Your private life is your own affair.

37:09.291 --> 37:11.416
No, I don't know that about you, Alan.

37:11.500 --> 37:12.416
I-I…

37:13.291 --> 37:15.708
don't care what people do
as long as they don't do it in public

37:15.791 --> 37:18.083
or try to force their ways
on the whole world.

37:18.166 --> 37:20.208
What were you crying about
on the telephone?

37:20.291 --> 37:24.333
All I-- All I can say is
please forgive me for making…

37:25.166 --> 37:26.750
such an ass of myself.

37:26.833 --> 37:29.083
You must have been upset
or you wouldn't have said you were

37:29.166 --> 37:31.125
and that you wanted to see me,
you had to see me.

37:31.208 --> 37:33.583
-Michael, please.
-Is something wrong between you and Fran?

37:33.666 --> 37:35.166
Listen, I've really gotta go.

37:35.250 --> 37:36.333
Why are you in New York?

37:36.416 --> 37:38.916
-Late for this dinner.
-Whose dinner? Where are you going?

37:39.000 --> 37:40.250
-Is that the loo?
-Yes.

37:40.791 --> 37:41.958
Excuse me.

37:50.791 --> 37:53.333
What's going on in here?
Oh, Mary, don't ask.

37:53.916 --> 37:55.875
Hank, why don't you come and join us?

37:56.916 --> 37:59.958
That's an interesting suggestion.
Whose idea is that?

38:00.583 --> 38:02.583
-Mine.

38:02.666 --> 38:04.458
He means in conversation.

38:04.541 --> 38:08.291
-Where are the rest of the wine glasses?
-I's working as fast as I can.

38:09.916 --> 38:11.666
- To your health.
- Up yours.

38:12.500 --> 38:13.583
Up my health?

38:14.166 --> 38:16.625
-Where's the gent?
-He's in the gent's room.

38:16.708 --> 38:18.875
If you can all hang on
for five more minutes,

38:18.958 --> 38:20.208
he's about to leave.

38:20.291 --> 38:22.083
-Well, at last.

38:27.208 --> 38:29.083
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

38:29.166 --> 38:30.958
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

38:31.041 --> 38:34.958
<i>♪ Happy birthday, dear Harold</i>
<i>Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

38:35.916 --> 38:37.000
Oh!

38:40.625 --> 38:42.083
Who the hell are you?

38:42.166 --> 38:44.833
She's Harold's present from me
and she's early,

38:44.916 --> 38:47.458
and that's not even Harold, you idiot!

38:47.541 --> 38:49.208
You said whoever answered the door.

38:49.875 --> 38:53.666
But not until midnight.
He's supposed to be a midnight cowboy.

38:54.833 --> 38:57.666
He looks right out of the chorus
of a bus-and-truck <i>Oklahoma!</i>

38:57.750 --> 39:01.041
Not until midnight, and you're supposed
to sing to the right person.

39:01.125 --> 39:05.083
I told you Harold
has very tight, tight, black curly hair.

39:05.166 --> 39:07.041
This number's practically bald.

39:07.125 --> 39:09.291
Thank you, and fuck you!

39:09.375 --> 39:10.875
Good thing I didn't open the door.

39:10.958 --> 39:13.958
-Not that tight and not that black.

39:14.041 --> 39:15.083
I-I forgot.

39:15.583 --> 39:17.666
Besides, I wanted to get
to the bars by midnight.

39:17.750 --> 39:20.000
Oh, he's a class act all the way around.

39:20.083 --> 39:21.708
What do you mean, "get to the bars"?

39:21.791 --> 39:24.041
Sweetie, I paid you
for the whole night, remember?

39:24.125 --> 39:27.291
I hurt my back doing my exercises,
and I wanted to get to bed early.

39:27.375 --> 39:29.875
Well, that's too bad. What happened?

39:29.958 --> 39:32.291
-I lost my grip doing my chin-ups,

39:32.375 --> 39:34.333
and I fell on my heels
and twisted my back.

39:34.416 --> 39:36.458
You shouldn't wear heels
when you do chin-ups!

39:38.833 --> 39:41.833
I shouldn't do chin-ups.
I got a weak grip.

39:41.916 --> 39:44.833
Aw, weak grip. In my day,
it used to be called a limp wrist.

39:44.916 --> 39:46.625
Who can remember that far back?

39:46.708 --> 39:49.666
-What's your card say?
-Here. Read it.

39:52.708 --> 39:56.000
"Dear Harold, bang-bang. You're alive."

39:56.083 --> 39:58.583
"Now roll over and play dead."

39:58.666 --> 40:01.125
-"Happy Birthday, Emory."

40:01.208 --> 40:02.958
Sheer poetry, Emmy.

40:03.041 --> 40:05.083
And in your usual good taste.

40:05.166 --> 40:08.333
So conservative of you
to resist a sign in Times Square.

40:10.541 --> 40:14.291
-Cheese it, here comes the socialite nun.
-Shit. God damn it, Emory.

40:17.916 --> 40:20.458
Well, I'm off.
Thanks, Michael, for the drink.

40:20.541 --> 40:23.041
Oh, you're entirely welcome.
So I'll see you tomorrow?

40:23.125 --> 40:27.208
No. No, I think I'm gonna be awfully busy.
Might even go back to Washington.

40:27.291 --> 40:30.125
-Got a heavy date in Lafayette Square?

40:30.208 --> 40:31.625
-What?
- Emory.

40:34.000 --> 40:35.041
Forget it.

40:37.000 --> 40:38.208
Are you Harold?

40:38.291 --> 40:41.083
No, he's not Harold. He's for Harold.

40:44.750 --> 40:48.000
-Goodbye, Hank. It was nice to meet you.
-Same here, Alan.

40:48.083 --> 40:50.125
If you're in Washington,
I'd like you to meet my wife.

40:50.208 --> 40:52.250
That'd be fun. Wouldn't it, Hank?

40:52.333 --> 40:54.833
Yeah, I'm sure they'd love to meet him…

40:54.916 --> 40:56.083
Her.

40:57.333 --> 41:00.791
I have such a problem with pronouns.

41:00.875 --> 41:02.833
How many S's are in the word pronoun?

41:04.625 --> 41:07.791
How'd you like to kiss my ass?
That's got two more S's in it.

41:08.833 --> 41:10.750
-How'd you like to blow me?
-Mmm.

41:11.583 --> 41:13.750
What's wrong with your wife?
She got lockjaw?

41:13.833 --> 41:15.750
Faggot! Fairy!

41:18.500 --> 41:20.791
-Emory!
- You goddamn freak.

41:28.041 --> 41:31.125
Motherfucker!
I'll kill you, you son of a bitch!

41:38.250 --> 41:40.416
Fucking faggot! Faggot!

41:41.166 --> 41:42.416
-Get some ice!
- Freak!

41:42.500 --> 41:44.208
What the hell is wrong with you, huh?

41:45.583 --> 41:46.625
Just relax.

41:46.708 --> 41:48.833
He just
busted your lip, love. Larry?

41:48.916 --> 41:50.291
-Here.

41:51.875 --> 41:53.583
- Jesus.
- Damn it.

42:00.166 --> 42:02.208
Do you mind waiting
over there with the gifts?

42:08.208 --> 42:11.375
Well, Harold! Happy birthday.

42:11.916 --> 42:13.625
You're just in time for the floor show,

42:14.208 --> 42:17.000
which you can see is on the floor.

42:17.083 --> 42:19.333
Hey, you, this is Harold.

42:20.250 --> 42:21.958
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

42:22.041 --> 42:25.583
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you</i>
<i>Happy birthday, dear Harold ♪</i>

42:25.666 --> 42:27.541
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

43:06.500 --> 43:08.250
What's so fucking funny?

43:13.166 --> 43:14.125
Life.

43:15.750 --> 43:19.375
Life is a goddamned laugh riot.
You remember life?

43:19.458 --> 43:21.666
-You're stoned.
-Happy birthday, Harold.

43:21.750 --> 43:23.750
You're stoned, and you're late.

43:23.833 --> 43:25.500
You were supposed
to arrive at this location

43:25.583 --> 43:28.291
at approximately 8:30 dash 9:00.

43:29.750 --> 43:31.166
What I am, Michael,

43:32.416 --> 43:37.416
is a 32-year-old,
ugly, pock-marked, Jew fairy,

43:38.125 --> 43:41.583
and if it takes me a while
to pull myself together,

43:42.166 --> 43:45.583
and if I smoke a little grass
before I can get up the nerve

43:45.666 --> 43:47.416
to show this face to the world,

43:48.541 --> 43:52.750
then it's nobody's
goddamn business but my own.

43:54.791 --> 43:56.625
And how are you this evening?

43:57.208 --> 43:58.958
Happy birthday, Hallie.

44:00.083 --> 44:02.166
- What happened to you?
-Don't ask.

44:02.250 --> 44:03.458
Your lips are turning blue.

44:03.541 --> 44:05.458
You look like
you've been rimming a snowman.

44:05.541 --> 44:07.458
That piss-elegant kooze hit me.

44:07.541 --> 44:10.666
Careful, Emory. That kind of talk
just makes him so nervous.

44:10.750 --> 44:11.875
Who is she?

44:12.458 --> 44:13.666
Who was she?

44:14.333 --> 44:16.375
Who does she hope to be?

44:16.458 --> 44:18.208
Who knows? Who cares?

44:18.291 --> 44:20.166
His name is Alan McCarthy.

44:21.416 --> 44:25.666
Not the famous college chum?
Is this my surprise from you, Michael?

44:25.750 --> 44:27.791
I think Alan is the one
who got the surprise.

44:27.875 --> 44:31.625
- You'll notice he's speechless.
-I hope she's in shock! She's a beast!

44:32.458 --> 44:33.875
Is it his birthday, too?

44:33.958 --> 44:36.916
- That's your surprise.
-Speaking of beasts.

44:37.000 --> 44:39.000
From me to you, darling.
How do you like it?

44:39.083 --> 44:42.625
Well, I suppose
he has an interesting face and body,

44:42.708 --> 44:46.583
but it turns me right off 'cause
he can't talk intelligently about art.

44:46.666 --> 44:48.500
Yeah, ain't it a shame?

44:48.583 --> 44:51.416
-I could never love anyone like that.
-Never. Who could?

44:51.500 --> 44:54.416
I could and you could, that's who could.

44:54.500 --> 44:56.291
Mary, she's gorgeous.

44:56.875 --> 44:59.250
She may be dumb, but she's all yours.

44:59.333 --> 45:03.125
I think my present is a super surprise.
I'm so thrilled to get it.

45:03.208 --> 45:06.583
I would kiss you,
but I don't want to get blood all over me.

45:06.666 --> 45:08.500
Look at my top!

45:09.250 --> 45:11.250
Wait till you see your face.

45:11.333 --> 45:14.625
Come on, Emory. Let's clean you up, hmm?
Happy birthday, Harold.

45:15.250 --> 45:17.541
-Thanks, love.
- Top is ruined.

45:17.625 --> 45:19.291
Take one of mine
from the bedroom.

45:19.375 --> 45:21.166
The one on the floor is vicuña.

45:22.250 --> 45:25.250
Just another birthday party
with the folks.

45:26.416 --> 45:30.541
Here's a cold bottle of Pouilly-Fuissé
I bought especially for you, kiddo.

45:30.625 --> 45:34.208
Pussycat, all is forgiven. You can stay.

45:34.791 --> 45:39.208
No. You can stay,
but not all is forgiven. Cheers.

45:44.958 --> 45:48.125
Who asked Mr. Right
to celebrate my birthday?

45:49.125 --> 45:50.916
There are no accidents.

45:51.666 --> 45:53.000
And who asked him?

45:54.541 --> 45:55.375
Guilty.

45:56.041 --> 45:58.375
Always got to have
your crutch, haven't you?

45:58.458 --> 45:59.708
I'm not leaving.

45:59.791 --> 46:02.541
I feel sick. I think I'm gonna throw up.

46:02.625 --> 46:05.875
Say that again, and I won't
have to take my appetite suppressants.

46:05.958 --> 46:09.250
-Easy does it. One step at a time.

46:20.125 --> 46:23.125
I am not ready
for my close-up, Mr. DeMille.

46:25.583 --> 46:27.750
Nor will I be for the next two weeks.

46:27.833 --> 46:30.958
Oh, my God! He's after me again!

46:31.041 --> 46:33.458
-He's sick.
-Yeah, sick in the head.

46:35.833 --> 46:38.125
Mary, take me home.
These queens are crazy.

46:40.666 --> 46:41.833
Turning on.

46:45.791 --> 46:48.958
-Anybody care to join me?
-Many thanks. No.

46:49.875 --> 46:51.250
No, thank you.

46:51.875 --> 46:54.041
How about you, Tex?

46:54.666 --> 46:55.625
Yeah.

46:57.125 --> 47:01.583
Michael, I left the casserole
in the oven. Take it out anytime.

47:01.666 --> 47:02.750
You're not going.

47:02.833 --> 47:05.750
- I couldn't eat now anyway.
-Well, I'm absolutely starving.

47:05.833 --> 47:07.416
I'll eat until I have a fat attack.

47:07.500 --> 47:09.541
I said you're not going.

47:09.625 --> 47:11.250
Beware the hostile fag.

47:11.333 --> 47:14.583
When he's sober, he's dangerous.
When he drinks, he's lethal.

47:14.666 --> 47:17.625
-Attention must not be paid.
- Well, I'm starved, Em.

47:17.708 --> 47:21.666
I'm ready for some of your
Alice B. Toklas' opium-baked lasagna.

47:21.750 --> 47:24.375
Are you really? Aw.

47:24.458 --> 47:27.458
That makes me so pleased.
Maybe I'll serve it before I leave.

47:27.541 --> 47:30.291
Nobody is going anywhere.

47:31.458 --> 47:34.041
You're gonna have schmertz tomorrow
you wouldn't believe.

47:34.125 --> 47:36.500
-Hey, do a figure-eight on that.

47:37.416 --> 47:41.291
I'm turning on. You're just turning.

47:41.375 --> 47:44.541
-Michael? Is there any air spray?
- Hairspray?

47:45.166 --> 47:48.666
You're supposed to be holding his head,
not doing his hair.

47:48.750 --> 47:50.083
Air spray, not hairspray.

47:50.166 --> 47:52.416
There's a can of floral spray
on top of the john.

47:52.500 --> 47:53.666
Thanks.

47:53.750 --> 47:57.000
I keep my grass
in the medicine cabinet in a Band-Aid box.

47:57.083 --> 47:58.833
Somebody told me it's the safest place.

47:58.916 --> 48:01.250
If the cops arrive,
you can lock yourself in the bathroom

48:01.333 --> 48:02.625
and flush it down the john.

48:02.708 --> 48:03.916
That's very cagey.

48:04.000 --> 48:05.833
Makes more sense
than where I was keeping it.

48:05.916 --> 48:08.208
In an oregano jar in the spice rack.

48:08.875 --> 48:13.000
I kept forgetting, and accidentally
turning my hateful mother on with a salad,

48:13.916 --> 48:15.083
but I think she likes it.

48:15.166 --> 48:18.625
No matter what meal she comes over for,
even if it's breakfast, she says,

48:18.708 --> 48:19.791
"Let's have a salad!"

48:25.250 --> 48:28.958
You are definitely the type
that still moves his lips when he reads,

48:29.625 --> 48:31.083
and who sits in a steam room

48:31.166 --> 48:33.583
and says things like,
"Hot enough for you?"

48:33.666 --> 48:36.250
I never use the steam room
when I go to the gym.

48:36.875 --> 48:39.208
It's bad after a workout.
It flattens you down.

48:40.541 --> 48:44.833
Just after you've broken your back
to blow yourself up like a poisoned dog?

48:46.416 --> 48:48.791
-Yeah.
- You're right, Harold.

48:49.833 --> 48:52.708
Not only can he not
talk intelligently about art,

48:52.791 --> 48:55.750
he can't even follow
from one sentence to the next.

48:56.625 --> 48:58.041
But he's beautiful.

48:58.916 --> 49:01.541
He has unnatural natural beauty.

49:02.208 --> 49:05.125
-Not that that means anything.
-It doesn't mean everything.

49:05.208 --> 49:08.708
Keep telling yourself that
as your hair drops out in handfuls.

49:09.541 --> 49:14.708
Not that it's not natural for one's hair
to recede as one reaches seniority.

49:15.750 --> 49:19.208
You know, faggots are worse
than women about their age.

49:19.291 --> 49:21.500
They think their lives are over at 30.

49:21.583 --> 49:24.708
Physical beauty
is not that goddamned important.

49:24.791 --> 49:27.041
Well, of course it's not. How could it be?

49:27.125 --> 49:29.041
It's only in the eye of the beholder.

49:29.125 --> 49:33.375
And it's only skin-deep.
Don't forget about that one.

49:34.833 --> 49:37.791
Oh, no,
I haven't forgotten that one at all.

49:38.291 --> 49:42.375
It's only skin-deep,
and it's transitory, too.

49:42.458 --> 49:44.708
It's terribly transitory.

49:44.791 --> 49:50.416
I mean, how long does it last?
30 or 40 or 50 years at the most?

49:50.500 --> 49:54.833
Yes, it's too bad
about this poor boy's face.

49:55.833 --> 49:57.000
It's tragic.

49:57.625 --> 49:59.875
He's absolutely cursed.

50:01.041 --> 50:04.916
And how could his beauty
ever compare with my soul?

50:05.666 --> 50:07.625
And although I have never seen my soul,

50:07.708 --> 50:10.875
I understand from my mother's rabbi
that it's a knockout.

50:11.791 --> 50:14.791
I, however, cannot seem
to locate it for a gander,

50:14.875 --> 50:17.833
and if I could,
I would sell it in a flash

50:17.916 --> 50:21.750
for some skin-deep,
transitory, meaningless beauty.

50:21.833 --> 50:24.541
Forgive him, Father,
for he know not what he do.

50:24.625 --> 50:27.125
Oh, Michael, you kill me.

50:27.208 --> 50:29.083
You don't know
which side of the fence you're on.

50:29.166 --> 50:31.708
If somebody says something pro-religion,
you're against them.

50:31.791 --> 50:34.166
If somebody denies God,
you're against them.

50:34.833 --> 50:37.333
One might say
you have a problem in this area.

50:37.416 --> 50:39.791
You can't live with it,
you can't live without it.

50:39.875 --> 50:41.458
-Hot stuff coming through!
-Hey!

50:41.541 --> 50:44.625
You know what? One could murder you
with very little effort.

50:44.708 --> 50:48.708
You hang on to that great
insurance policy called the church.

50:48.791 --> 50:50.541
That's right, I believe in God.

50:50.625 --> 50:54.416
And if it turns out that there
really isn't one? Okay, nothing lost.

50:54.500 --> 50:57.208
But if it turns out that there is,
I'm covered.

50:57.291 --> 50:59.958
Harriet Hypocrite, that's who you are.

51:00.041 --> 51:03.000
Right. I am one
of those truly rotten Catholics

51:03.083 --> 51:06.791
who gets drunk, sins all night,
and goes to Mass the next morning.

51:06.875 --> 51:09.541
It depends on what you think sin is.

51:09.625 --> 51:13.458
Would you shut your minty mouth
and get back to the goddamn kitchen?

51:14.875 --> 51:17.333
Say whatever you want. Just don't hit me.

51:18.708 --> 51:21.333
Well, is it bigger than a breadstick?

51:21.416 --> 51:23.250
He's laying down for a little bit.

51:23.333 --> 51:25.625
-How does the bathroom smell?
-Better.

51:25.708 --> 51:28.000
-Before it smelled like somebody puked.

51:28.083 --> 51:30.583
Now it smells like somebody
puked in a gardenia patch.

51:30.666 --> 51:32.666
Dinner is served!

51:35.083 --> 51:36.666
What would you like, big boy?

51:36.750 --> 51:39.291
Alan McCarthy, and don't hold the mayo.

51:39.375 --> 51:42.833
Oh, Em, it looks absolutely fabulous.

51:42.916 --> 51:44.583
I'd make somebody a good wife.

51:44.666 --> 51:46.583
-What is it?
-Lasagna.

51:46.666 --> 51:49.833
Looks like spaghetti and meatballs
sort of flattened out.

51:51.166 --> 51:54.041
-Well, it's been in the steam room.

51:54.125 --> 51:55.833
-It has?
-Oh, my God.

51:56.500 --> 52:00.458
"It looks like spaghetti and meatballs
sort of flattened out."

52:00.541 --> 52:02.916
Oh, yes, Harold, truly enviable.

52:03.000 --> 52:06.833
As opposed to you,
who knows so much about haute cuisine.

52:06.916 --> 52:10.458
Raconteur, gourmet, troll.

52:11.083 --> 52:12.875
-It's good.
-You like it? Eat it.

52:12.958 --> 52:14.875
Stuff your mouth
so you can't say anything.

52:14.958 --> 52:15.791
Turning.

52:15.875 --> 52:17.416
- Wine?
- No, thank you.

52:17.500 --> 52:19.833
Oh, go on, kiddo. Force yourself.

52:19.916 --> 52:23.541
Have a little <i>vin ordinaire</i>
to wash down all that depressed pasta.

52:23.625 --> 52:27.333
Sommelier, connoisseur, pig.

52:28.250 --> 52:29.708
Aren't you gonna have any?

52:29.791 --> 52:33.750
No, my lip hurts too much to eat.
Anybody gonna bring a plate up to Alan?

52:33.833 --> 52:37.833
Oh. The punching bag
is now dissolved into Flo Nightingale.

52:37.916 --> 52:39.375
Do you like it, Hallie?

52:39.458 --> 52:42.750
Mmm. I'm having seconds and thirds
and maybe even fifths.

52:42.833 --> 52:45.250
I'm absolutely desperate
to keep the weight up.

52:46.708 --> 52:50.083
You're absolutely paranoid
about absolutely everything.

52:50.166 --> 52:54.125
Oh, yeah? Well, why don't you
not tell me about it?

52:54.916 --> 52:57.125
You starve yourself all day

52:57.208 --> 52:59.625
so that you can
gorge yourself at one meal,

52:59.708 --> 53:04.500
and then you moan and groan about
how fat you are and how ugly you are,

53:04.583 --> 53:08.000
when the truth is you're no fatter
or thinner than you ever were.

53:08.083 --> 53:10.333
-Polly Paranoia.
-This is great, Emory.

53:10.416 --> 53:13.666
Connie Casserole. No trouble at all.
Oh, Mary, don't ask.

53:13.750 --> 53:18.250
Oh! Oh! And this pathological lateness,
that's downright crazy.

53:18.333 --> 53:19.333
Turning!

53:19.416 --> 53:22.291
Standing before a bathroom mirror
for hours and hours

53:22.375 --> 53:24.791
before you can walk out on the street,

53:24.875 --> 53:29.041
and looking no different
after Christ knows how many applications

53:29.125 --> 53:33.916
of Christ knows how many
ointments and salves and creams and masks.

53:34.000 --> 53:37.208
I've got bad skin. What can I tell you?

53:37.291 --> 53:40.041
Who wouldn't after they deliberately
take a pair of tweezers

53:40.125 --> 53:42.791
and deliberately mutilate their pores?

53:42.875 --> 53:44.666
There's no wonder
you got holes in your face

53:44.750 --> 53:48.583
after the hack job you have done
on yourself year in and year out.

53:48.666 --> 53:50.916
King of the pig people.

53:51.000 --> 53:54.041
Yes, you've got scars on your face,
but they're not that bad.

53:54.125 --> 53:56.041
And if you'd leave yourself alone,

53:56.125 --> 53:59.125
you wouldn't have any more
than you've already awarded yourself.

54:00.541 --> 54:03.916
You'd really like me
to compliment you now, wouldn't you,

54:04.000 --> 54:05.333
for how honest you're being?

54:06.458 --> 54:08.250
For being my best friend who will tell me

54:08.333 --> 54:12.458
what even my best friends won't tell me,
you hateful sow.

54:12.541 --> 54:14.625
And the pills!

54:14.708 --> 54:16.958
Harold has been gathering, saving,

54:17.041 --> 54:19.708
and storing up barbiturates
for the past year

54:19.791 --> 54:21.375
like a goddamn squirrel.

54:21.458 --> 54:24.375
Hundreds of Nembutals,
hundreds of Seconals.

54:24.458 --> 54:26.250
All in preparation for,

54:26.333 --> 54:30.291
and anticipation of,
the long winter of his death.

54:30.375 --> 54:31.958
I'll tell you right now, Hallie,

54:32.041 --> 54:35.416
when the time comes,
you'll never have the guts.

54:36.041 --> 54:38.333
It's not always like it happens in plays.

54:38.416 --> 54:42.000
Not all faggots bump themselves off
at the end of the story.

54:46.625 --> 54:49.208
-What you say may be true.

54:50.208 --> 54:52.416
Time will undoubtedly tell.

54:53.333 --> 54:56.333
But in the meantime,
you've left out one detail.

54:58.375 --> 55:01.666
The cosmetics
and astringents are paid for,

55:02.625 --> 55:05.208
the bathroom is paid for,

55:05.916 --> 55:07.666
the tweezers are paid for,

55:07.750 --> 55:12.625
and the pills… are paid for.

55:19.125 --> 55:22.166
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

55:22.250 --> 55:26.625
- Oh, Jesus.
-<i>♪ Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

55:26.708 --> 55:30.750
<i>♪ Happy birthday, dear Harold ♪</i>

55:32.458 --> 55:34.666
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

55:34.750 --> 55:36.041
You're so sweet.

55:37.000 --> 55:39.541
Blow out the candles, Mary,
and make a wish!

55:39.625 --> 55:41.083
Blow out your candles, Laura.

55:49.583 --> 55:53.125
- She's 32 years young!
- Oh, my God.

55:53.208 --> 55:56.041
-Now you have to open your gifts.
-Start with this one.

55:56.125 --> 55:59.041
Presents! Where's the card?

55:59.125 --> 56:01.083
-Uh…
- Here.

56:01.875 --> 56:04.291
-Oh, from Larry.
- Larry.

56:04.375 --> 56:06.083
Why would you put it on the back?

56:09.375 --> 56:14.208
Oh, it's heaven.
Oh, I just love it, Larry.

56:14.291 --> 56:16.875
-What is it?
-The deed to Boardwalk.

56:16.958 --> 56:19.375
- Aw. Gay pop art.

56:20.083 --> 56:22.666
Oh, Larry, it's super.
It goes up the minute I get home.

56:22.750 --> 56:24.166
-Oh, good.
- I don't get it.

56:24.250 --> 56:25.958
You cruise Atlantic City or something?

56:26.875 --> 56:28.583
How much did you pay for him?

56:29.250 --> 56:33.375
-He was a steal.
-I'm not a steal. I cost $20.

56:35.583 --> 56:38.291
And what do you do for $20?

56:38.875 --> 56:39.958
I do my best.

56:40.041 --> 56:43.416
Oh, what a nifty sweater.

56:44.416 --> 56:45.625
Thank you, Hank.

56:45.708 --> 56:47.750
You can take it back,
exchange it for something else.

56:47.833 --> 56:52.833
-No, I think this one is just… nifty.

56:54.166 --> 56:55.791
-Who wants cake?
- Everybody?

56:55.875 --> 56:56.791
None for me.

56:56.875 --> 56:58.291
-There you go.
-Thanks.

56:58.875 --> 57:02.208
Oh, Bernard! How divine!

57:02.291 --> 57:05.083
Look, everybody, bejeweled knee pads.

57:07.666 --> 57:08.958
Monogrammed.

57:09.541 --> 57:11.166
Bernard, you're a camp!

57:23.125 --> 57:24.333
Thank you, Michael.

57:25.083 --> 57:26.000
What?

57:27.458 --> 57:28.458
Oh.

57:30.750 --> 57:33.333
-You're welcome.
- What is it, Harold?

57:34.083 --> 57:36.375
It's a photograph of him
in a silver frame,

57:36.458 --> 57:39.166
and there's an inscription engraved
and the date.

57:39.958 --> 57:41.000
What's it say?

57:46.750 --> 57:48.458
Just something personal.

57:51.041 --> 57:54.875
Hey, Bernard, what do you say we have
a little music to liven things up?

57:54.958 --> 57:58.333
-Okay.
-Yeah, I feel like dancing.

58:00.583 --> 58:01.625
Come on, Michael.

58:02.458 --> 58:04.375
Oh, no, thanks. I can only lead.

58:05.166 --> 58:08.958
- I can follow.
-Oh, I think I'll sip this one out.

58:09.041 --> 58:09.875
Ha!

58:17.708 --> 58:20.625
<i>♪ You see this guy? ♪</i>

58:22.458 --> 58:26.291
<i>♪ This guy's in love with you ♪</i>

58:29.083 --> 58:31.916
<i>♪ Yes, I'm in love ♪</i>

58:33.791 --> 58:39.000
<i>♪ Who looks at you the way I do? ♪</i>

58:39.791 --> 58:44.833
<i>♪ When you smile I can tell ♪</i>

58:44.916 --> 58:50.500
<i>♪ We know each other very well ♪</i>

58:51.083 --> 58:55.541
<i>♪ How can I show you ♪</i>

58:56.708 --> 59:02.291
<i>♪ I'm glad I got to know you? ♪</i>

59:02.375 --> 59:06.583
<i>♪ 'Cause I've heard some talk ♪</i>

59:06.666 --> 59:07.666
Come on, Tex.

59:08.333 --> 59:12.125
<i>-♪ They say you think I'm fine ♪</i>
-You're on.

59:14.875 --> 59:17.958
<i>♪ Yes, I'm in love ♪</i>

59:19.750 --> 59:25.166
<i>♪ And what I'd do to make you mine ♪</i>

59:25.666 --> 59:30.833
<i>♪ Tell me now, is it so? ♪</i>

59:30.916 --> 59:36.333
<i>♪ Don't let me be the last to know ♪</i>

59:36.416 --> 59:41.375
<i>♪ My hands are shaking ♪</i>

59:42.625 --> 59:48.166
<i>♪ Don't let my heart keep breaking ♪</i>

59:48.250 --> 59:52.500
<i>♪ 'Cause I need your love ♪</i>

59:54.875 --> 59:58.000
<i>♪ I want your love ♪</i>

1:00:00.666 --> 1:00:03.250
<i>♪ Say you're in love ♪</i>

1:00:04.666 --> 1:00:08.583
<i>♪ In love with this guy ♪</i>

1:00:13.291 --> 1:00:17.541
<i>♪ If not, I'll just die ♪</i>

1:00:17.625 --> 1:00:19.041
Shit.

1:00:20.958 --> 1:00:22.916
-Michael!
- Everybody, help clean up.

1:00:26.916 --> 1:00:28.791
Go, go, go! Come on!

1:00:33.583 --> 1:00:36.250
-Come here, kid.

1:00:39.833 --> 1:00:42.625
- Everybody, hurry up!
- Close the door!

1:00:44.375 --> 1:00:46.208
- Come on, guys.
- Come on.

1:00:47.791 --> 1:00:49.166
Get the fuck inside.

1:00:50.000 --> 1:00:51.875
- Oh God.

1:00:51.958 --> 1:00:53.208
I'm dripping all over.

1:00:55.083 --> 1:00:57.208
Take a towel.
Don't get the goddamn furniture wet.

1:00:57.291 --> 1:01:00.458
-Here. Towel. Dry off.
-Jesus, Michael.

1:01:00.541 --> 1:01:02.125
-Thanks. Thanks, Michael.

1:01:05.208 --> 1:01:06.208
Wanna dance?

1:01:06.291 --> 1:01:08.833
Uh-oh, Yvonne the Terrible is back.

1:01:09.500 --> 1:01:11.833
Oh, hello, Alan. You feel better?

1:01:13.458 --> 1:01:15.791
Oh, no. No, no, no. Alan, no.

1:01:16.500 --> 1:01:20.833
As they say in the Deep South,
don't rush off in this inclement weather.

1:01:20.916 --> 1:01:22.250
You'll never get a cab.

1:01:22.333 --> 1:01:24.416
Revolution complete.

1:01:24.500 --> 1:01:27.916
You missed the cake
and you missed the opening of the gifts,

1:01:28.000 --> 1:01:29.500
but you're still in luck.

1:01:29.583 --> 1:01:32.208
You're just in time for a party game.

1:01:32.291 --> 1:01:34.125
Hey, everybody, game time.

1:01:34.208 --> 1:01:36.291
Michael, why don't you just let him go?

1:01:36.916 --> 1:01:38.333
He can go if he wants to,

1:01:39.083 --> 1:01:41.375
but not before we play a little game.

1:01:41.458 --> 1:01:43.708
What's it gonna be, movie-star gin?

1:01:43.791 --> 1:01:48.625
No. No, that's too faggy for Alan to play.
He wouldn't be any good at it.

1:01:48.708 --> 1:01:50.958
What would you like to play, Michael?
The Truth Game?

1:01:51.541 --> 1:01:52.458
Cute, Hallie.

1:01:52.541 --> 1:01:54.583
Or would you like to play Murder?

1:01:54.666 --> 1:01:57.750
-You all remember that one, don't you?
- Very, very cute.

1:01:57.833 --> 1:01:59.625
As I recall, they're quite similar.

1:01:59.708 --> 1:02:02.416
The rules are the same in both:
you kill somebody.

1:02:03.291 --> 1:02:05.250
-Mickey, I'm leaving.
-Stay where you are.

1:02:05.333 --> 1:02:08.958
-Michael, let him go.
- He really doesn't want to.

1:02:09.041 --> 1:02:11.750
If he did, he'd have left a long time ago,

1:02:11.833 --> 1:02:13.750
or he wouldn't have come
in the first place.

1:02:13.833 --> 1:02:16.291
-Mickey. I don't feel--
-My name is Michael.

1:02:17.000 --> 1:02:17.958
I'm called Michael.

1:02:18.625 --> 1:02:21.500
You must never call
anyone called Michael "Mickey."

1:02:22.625 --> 1:02:26.000
Those of us who are named Michael
get very nervous about it.

1:02:27.541 --> 1:02:29.166
If you don't believe it, try it.

1:02:30.875 --> 1:02:32.208
I'm sorry. I…

1:02:33.875 --> 1:02:35.333
I can't think.

1:02:35.416 --> 1:02:36.958
You can think.

1:02:37.916 --> 1:02:39.500
What you can't do is leave.

1:02:39.583 --> 1:02:41.750
It's like watching
an accident on a highway.

1:02:41.833 --> 1:02:44.333
You can't look at it,
and you can't look away.

1:03:07.791 --> 1:03:10.041
Who's going to play
with Alan and me? Everyone?

1:03:10.125 --> 1:03:13.875
-I have no intention of playing.
-Yeah, nor do I.

1:03:13.958 --> 1:03:16.125
Well, not everyone
is a participant in life.

1:03:16.208 --> 1:03:19.083
There are always those
who stand on the sidelines and watch.

1:03:19.166 --> 1:03:21.708
-What's the game?
- Simply this:

1:03:22.500 --> 1:03:25.250
We all have to call on the telephone

1:03:25.333 --> 1:03:29.916
the one person
we truly believe we have loved.

1:03:31.791 --> 1:03:34.625
-I'm not playing.
-Oh, yes, you are.

1:03:35.250 --> 1:03:37.916
-You'd like for me to play.
-I'd like to know who you'd call

1:03:38.000 --> 1:03:40.375
after all the fancy speeches
I've heard lately.

1:03:40.458 --> 1:03:42.875
Who'd you call, Hank? Would you call me?

1:03:42.958 --> 1:03:46.291
Oh! Sounds like there's,
how you say, trouble in paradise.

1:03:46.375 --> 1:03:49.250
Well, if there isn't,
I'm sure you could stir up some.

1:03:49.333 --> 1:03:51.375
And who would you call? Hmm?

1:03:52.041 --> 1:03:54.458
Don't think I think for one minute
that it would be me.

1:03:55.166 --> 1:03:57.583
Or that one call would do it.
You'd have to make several.

1:03:57.666 --> 1:04:00.250
Three long-distance,
God only knows how many locals.

1:04:00.333 --> 1:04:02.833
-I'm glad I don't have to pay the bill.
-Quiet.

1:04:02.916 --> 1:04:05.833
Don't worry.
Michael won't pay it either.

1:04:06.375 --> 1:04:10.875
Now, here's how it works.
If you make the call, you get one point.

1:04:10.958 --> 1:04:13.958
If the person you are calling answers,
you get two more points.

1:04:14.041 --> 1:04:16.041
Somebody else answers, you only get one.

1:04:16.125 --> 1:04:18.375
And if there's no answer at all…

1:04:18.958 --> 1:04:19.958
you're screwed.

1:04:20.041 --> 1:04:21.833
You're screwed if you make the call.

1:04:21.916 --> 1:04:24.750
When you get the person
whom you are calling on the line,

1:04:24.833 --> 1:04:28.208
if you tell them who you are,
you get two points. And then…

1:04:29.625 --> 1:04:33.083
If you tell them that you love them,

1:04:33.166 --> 1:04:35.958
you get a bonus of five more points.

1:04:36.041 --> 1:04:37.625
-Hateful.

1:04:37.708 --> 1:04:41.416
Therefore, you can get
as many as ten points and as few as one.

1:04:41.500 --> 1:04:44.083
You can get as few as none
if you know how to work it.

1:04:44.166 --> 1:04:45.541
Hank, leave with me?

1:04:45.625 --> 1:04:47.750
Oh, well, now, did you hear that?

1:04:51.500 --> 1:04:53.708
You don't understand, Alan. I can't.

1:04:54.583 --> 1:04:57.166
You can, but I can't.

1:04:57.250 --> 1:04:59.666
If he doesn't understand,
explain it to him.

1:04:59.750 --> 1:05:01.833
-I'll explain it.
-I had a feeling you might.

1:05:01.916 --> 1:05:04.416
Alan, Hank and Larry are lovers.

1:05:05.083 --> 1:05:06.500
They're not roommates.

1:05:06.583 --> 1:05:08.583
-Bedmates, lovers.
-Michael.

1:05:08.666 --> 1:05:11.583
No man's still got a roommate
when he's over 40 years old.

1:05:11.666 --> 1:05:13.583
If they're not lovers, they're sisters.

1:05:13.666 --> 1:05:16.583
-Hank is the one who's over 40.
-Well, you're pushing it.

1:05:17.541 --> 1:05:18.708
Hank.

1:05:21.166 --> 1:05:24.625
Yes, Alan. Larry and I are lovers.

1:05:24.708 --> 1:05:25.541
But…

1:05:26.791 --> 1:05:27.875
But you're married.

1:05:31.875 --> 1:05:33.125
Jesus Christ.

1:05:34.916 --> 1:05:37.625
I think you said the wrong thing.

1:05:37.708 --> 1:05:40.000
Don't you love that quaint little idea?

1:05:40.083 --> 1:05:43.500
If a man's married,
he's automatically heterosexual.

1:05:43.583 --> 1:05:49.708
Alan, Hank swings both ways…
with a definite preference.

1:05:55.416 --> 1:05:58.791
Now… who makes the first call?

1:06:03.208 --> 1:06:05.291
-Emory?
-You go, Bernard.

1:06:05.375 --> 1:06:08.958
-Mm. I don't want to.
-Go on, call up Peter Dahlbeck.

1:06:09.041 --> 1:06:12.000
-That's who you'd like to call, isn't it?
- Who is Peter Dahlbeck?

1:06:12.083 --> 1:06:13.208
The boy in Detroit

1:06:13.291 --> 1:06:15.583
whose family Bernard's mother
has been a laundress for

1:06:15.666 --> 1:06:18.208
since he was a little black-eyed pea.

1:06:20.541 --> 1:06:21.958
I worked for them, too,

1:06:23.083 --> 1:06:24.958
after school and every summer.

1:06:28.666 --> 1:06:30.416
I think I've loved him all my life.

1:06:33.958 --> 1:06:36.083
<i>But he never knew I was alive.</i>

1:06:42.416 --> 1:06:43.958
Besides, he's straight.

1:06:44.041 --> 1:06:45.750
Nothing ever happened between you?

1:06:46.541 --> 1:06:49.083
They finally made it
in the pool house one night

1:06:49.166 --> 1:06:51.083
after a drunken swimming party.

1:06:51.166 --> 1:06:55.458
With the right wine and the right music,
there are damn few that aren't curious.

1:06:55.541 --> 1:06:58.833
And afterwards, we went swimming,

1:06:59.666 --> 1:07:04.333
in the nude, in the dark,
only the moon reflecting the water.

1:07:04.416 --> 1:07:06.166
How romantic.

1:07:06.250 --> 1:07:10.500
And the next morning, you took him
his coffee and Alka-Seltzer on a tray.

1:07:13.125 --> 1:07:16.666
I remember I was worried sick all morning
about having to face him,

1:07:17.458 --> 1:07:20.166
but he pretended
like nothing at all had happened.

1:07:20.250 --> 1:07:23.791
Christ, he must have been so drunk,
he didn't remember a thing.

1:07:23.875 --> 1:07:25.416
Odd how that works.

1:07:25.500 --> 1:07:29.458
And now for ten points,
get that liar on the phone.

1:07:34.416 --> 1:07:36.583
- Mmm!
- Oh!

1:07:43.791 --> 1:07:45.041
You know the number?

1:07:46.083 --> 1:07:49.541
Sure, he's back
in Grosse Pointe, living at home.

1:07:49.625 --> 1:07:51.875
Just got separated from his third wife.

1:07:51.958 --> 1:07:53.166
-Mmm-hmm.
- Mmm-hmm.

1:08:00.541 --> 1:08:02.458
-DA or BY?
-What?

1:08:02.541 --> 1:08:05.625
It's operator lingo.
It means "doesn't answer" or "busy."

1:08:05.708 --> 1:08:07.750
He didn't even give it time
to find out.

1:08:07.833 --> 1:08:11.791
Come on, Bernard. Pick up that phone.

1:08:11.875 --> 1:08:15.166
You know you want to call him.
You know that, don't you?

1:08:16.333 --> 1:08:17.333
Well, go ahead.

1:08:18.125 --> 1:08:22.291
Your curiosity's got the best of you now.
So go on, call him.

1:08:44.541 --> 1:08:45.541
Do it.

1:08:56.916 --> 1:08:58.416
-Hello?
- One point.

1:08:59.125 --> 1:09:00.333
Who's speaking?

1:09:03.125 --> 1:09:04.125
Oh!

1:09:04.958 --> 1:09:07.208
-Mrs. Dahlbeck.
- One point.

1:09:07.291 --> 1:09:08.291
It's Bernard.

1:09:11.041 --> 1:09:12.291
Francine's boy.

1:09:13.166 --> 1:09:15.208
- Son, not boy.
-Shh.

1:09:17.833 --> 1:09:20.750
Oh, just fine, thank you.

1:09:22.375 --> 1:09:25.666
Mrs. Dahlbeck, is-is… Peter at home?

1:09:30.041 --> 1:09:31.166
Oh.

1:09:33.708 --> 1:09:34.583
Oh, I see.

1:09:34.666 --> 1:09:35.666
Oh, shit.

1:09:36.166 --> 1:09:38.000
-Oh, no, no.

1:09:38.583 --> 1:09:42.125
Oh, no, no. No, no.
It-It's nothing important. I, um…

1:09:45.708 --> 1:09:47.458
I just wanted to tell him that…

1:09:51.750 --> 1:09:54.833
<i>Just to tell him that I…</i>

1:09:54.916 --> 1:09:59.708
I love him… and I've always loved him.

1:10:06.125 --> 1:10:08.916
That I was very sorry
to hear about him and his wife.

1:10:09.000 --> 1:10:10.041
No points.

1:10:11.708 --> 1:10:13.125
Mama wrote me.

1:10:15.333 --> 1:10:19.166
Yes, it is. It-It-It really is. Well, uh…

1:10:21.291 --> 1:10:25.416
Would you just tell him
that I called and said that I…

1:10:35.166 --> 1:10:36.166
That I, uh…

1:10:48.500 --> 1:10:50.333
I was just very, very sorry to hear

1:10:50.416 --> 1:10:52.916
and hope they can
get everything straightened out.

1:10:55.375 --> 1:10:57.750
Good night. Uh-huh.

1:10:58.666 --> 1:10:59.791
Goodbye.

1:11:14.000 --> 1:11:15.416
Two points total.

1:11:15.916 --> 1:11:18.125
-Terrible. Next.
-You all right, Bernard?

1:11:19.916 --> 1:11:20.833
Why did I call?

1:11:22.833 --> 1:11:24.166
Why did I do that?

1:11:24.958 --> 1:11:27.291
-Where was he?
-Out on a date.

1:11:29.958 --> 1:11:30.833
Come on.

1:11:31.333 --> 1:11:32.166
Emory.

1:11:34.166 --> 1:11:35.208
Punch in.

1:11:50.583 --> 1:11:52.458
May I have a number, please?

1:11:53.583 --> 1:11:54.708
In the Bronx.

1:11:57.041 --> 1:11:59.583
For a Delbert Botts.

1:11:59.666 --> 1:12:04.083
A Delbert Botts?
How many could there be?

1:12:04.166 --> 1:12:05.916
Wish I hadn't called now.

1:12:06.000 --> 1:12:07.750
No, the residence number, please.

1:12:18.708 --> 1:12:19.708
Thank you.

1:12:20.500 --> 1:12:23.125
I do wish Information
would stop calling me "ma'am."

1:12:23.208 --> 1:12:24.666
-Hey, by all means,

1:12:24.750 --> 1:12:26.375
scribble all over my phone.

1:12:26.458 --> 1:12:28.375
It comes off with a little spit.

1:12:28.458 --> 1:12:30.500
Ooh, like a lot of things.

1:12:30.583 --> 1:12:32.541
Who the hell is Delbert Botts?

1:12:32.625 --> 1:12:36.541
The one person I've always loved.
That's who you said to call, isn't it?

1:12:36.625 --> 1:12:37.541
Right, emery board.

1:12:37.625 --> 1:12:41.000
Ugh, how could you love somebody
with a name like that?

1:12:41.583 --> 1:12:46.625
Yes, Emory, you couldn't possibly
love anyone with a name like that.

1:12:46.708 --> 1:12:49.541
That wouldn't look good
on a place card. Right, Alan?

1:12:49.625 --> 1:12:51.500
I admit his name is not so good,

1:12:52.291 --> 1:12:53.250
but he…

1:12:54.416 --> 1:12:56.250
Absolutely beautiful.

1:12:56.333 --> 1:13:00.125
I've loved him ever since
the first day I laid eyes on him,

1:13:01.708 --> 1:13:04.125
which was when I was in the fifth grade

1:13:04.791 --> 1:13:08.291
and he was a senior.

1:13:10.791 --> 1:13:12.666
Then he went away to college,

1:13:12.750 --> 1:13:15.416
and by the time he got out,
I was in high school.

1:13:15.500 --> 1:13:18.875
And he had become… a dentist.

1:13:18.958 --> 1:13:22.958
And you went and had every tooth
in your head pulled out, right?

1:13:23.625 --> 1:13:24.541
No.

1:13:25.750 --> 1:13:27.875
I just had my teeth cleaned, that's all.

1:13:27.958 --> 1:13:31.000
-Oh, I shouldn't have called.
-Will you shut up, Bernard?

1:13:31.083 --> 1:13:34.208
And take your boring, sleep-making icks
somewhere else. Go.

1:13:35.208 --> 1:13:39.458
I remember I looked
right in his eyes the whole time.

1:13:41.291 --> 1:13:43.500
I kept wanting to bite his fingers.

1:13:43.583 --> 1:13:45.625
Well, it's absolutely mind-boggling.

1:13:45.708 --> 1:13:48.916
-Phyllis Phallic.
-It absolutely boggles the mind.

1:13:49.000 --> 1:13:51.833
I told him I was having my teeth cleaned

1:13:51.916 --> 1:13:56.833
for the junior-senior prom
for which I was in charge of decorations.

1:13:58.375 --> 1:14:00.833
<i>I told him</i>
<i>it was a celestial theme,</i>

1:14:00.916 --> 1:14:03.875
<i>and I was cutting stars out of tin foil</i>

1:14:03.958 --> 1:14:08.916
<i>and making clouds</i>
<i>out of chicken wire and angel's hair.</i>

1:14:10.541 --> 1:14:13.875
<i>Oh, Mary, it takes a fairy</i>
<i>to make something pretty.</i>

1:14:13.958 --> 1:14:17.125
I got angel's hair down my shirt
once at Christmastime.

1:14:17.208 --> 1:14:18.458
Gosh, did it itch.

1:14:19.041 --> 1:14:21.541
It would be terrible
if you got that stuff in your…

1:14:24.375 --> 1:14:25.333
I'll be quiet.

1:14:31.416 --> 1:14:35.166
He was engaged
to this stupid-ass girl named Loraine,

1:14:35.250 --> 1:14:37.708
whose mother was truly
a real see-you-next-Tuesday.

1:14:37.791 --> 1:14:39.750
Uh-uh. Don't digress.

1:14:41.166 --> 1:14:45.791
Well, anyway… I was a wreck.
I mean, a total mess.

1:14:45.875 --> 1:14:49.333
I couldn't eat, sleep,
stand up, sit down, nothing.

1:14:50.541 --> 1:14:54.500
Finally, I called him on the phone
and asked if I could see him alone.

1:14:55.375 --> 1:14:57.666
Clearly, not the coolest of moves.

1:14:58.708 --> 1:14:59.833
He said okay.

1:15:00.875 --> 1:15:02.458
Told me to come by his house.

1:15:04.791 --> 1:15:08.958
I was so nervous, my hands were shaking.
I couldn't even look at him.

1:15:09.791 --> 1:15:15.041
I just… stared straight in space
and blurted out why I'd come.

1:15:15.125 --> 1:15:18.500
I told him I wanted him to be my friend.

1:15:19.833 --> 1:15:24.166
I said that I had never
had a friend I could talk to

1:15:24.875 --> 1:15:28.583
and tell everything to and-and trust.

1:15:30.541 --> 1:15:32.291
I asked him if he would be my friend.

1:15:34.208 --> 1:15:36.291
He said he would be glad to be my friend,

1:15:36.875 --> 1:15:40.208
and anytime I wanted
to see him or call him,

1:15:40.291 --> 1:15:42.750
to just call him and he'd see me.

1:15:44.083 --> 1:15:48.166
And he shook my trembling hand,
and I left…

1:15:50.166 --> 1:15:53.125
-on a cloud.
-One of the ones you made yourself.

1:15:53.208 --> 1:15:54.291
And the next day,

1:15:55.083 --> 1:15:57.791
I went out and bought him
a gold-plated cigarette lighter

1:15:57.875 --> 1:15:59.958
and had his initials monogrammed on it.

1:16:00.041 --> 1:16:04.791
I wrote a card that said,
"From your friend, Emory."

1:16:05.375 --> 1:16:08.166
Seventeen years old
and already big with the gifts.

1:16:08.250 --> 1:16:09.958
And then the night of the prom,

1:16:10.833 --> 1:16:15.083
I heard Loraine
and another girl I knew giggling together.

1:16:17.708 --> 1:16:21.666
<i>Obviously, Del had told Loraine</i>
<i>about my calling and about the gift.</i>

1:16:22.833 --> 1:16:25.625
<i>Pretty soon, everybody at the dance</i>
<i>had heard about it.</i>

1:16:26.666 --> 1:16:28.791
<i>They were laughing and making jokes.</i>

1:16:30.791 --> 1:16:34.375
<i>Everybody knew</i>
<i>that I had a crush on Dr. Delbert Botts</i>

1:16:34.958 --> 1:16:37.500
<i>and that I had asked him to be my friend.</i>

1:16:44.208 --> 1:16:46.416
What they didn't know
was that I loved him,

1:16:48.375 --> 1:16:50.125
and that I would go on loving him

1:16:50.208 --> 1:16:55.833
years after they had all forgotten
my funny little secret.

1:16:57.916 --> 1:17:01.500
Well, I for one need an insulin injection.

1:17:01.583 --> 1:17:02.750
Oh.

1:17:07.083 --> 1:17:09.041
-Call him.
-Don't, Emory.

1:17:09.125 --> 1:17:10.958
Since when are you telling him what to do?

1:17:11.041 --> 1:17:13.166
Don't. You'll be sorry.
Take my word for it.

1:17:13.250 --> 1:17:14.875
What have I got to lose?

1:17:14.958 --> 1:17:17.416
Your dignity.
That's what you've got to lose.

1:17:17.500 --> 1:17:19.750
Oh, that's a knee-slapper. I love…

1:17:19.833 --> 1:17:21.791
You're telling him about dignity

1:17:21.875 --> 1:17:24.208
when you allow him
to degrade you constantly

1:17:24.291 --> 1:17:25.916
by Uncle Tom-ing you to death.

1:17:26.000 --> 1:17:30.166
He can do it, Michael.
I can do it. But you can't do it.

1:17:30.250 --> 1:17:33.583
Isn't that discrimination?

1:17:33.666 --> 1:17:36.833
I don't like it from him,
and I don't like it from me.

1:17:37.791 --> 1:17:39.458
But I do it to myself,

1:17:40.375 --> 1:17:42.083
and I let him do it.

1:17:42.166 --> 1:17:44.458
I let him do it
because it's the only thing that,

1:17:44.541 --> 1:17:46.333
to him, makes him my equal.

1:17:48.125 --> 1:17:50.500
We both got the short end of the stick,

1:17:50.583 --> 1:17:53.708
but I got a hell of a lot more
than he did, and he knows it.

1:17:53.791 --> 1:17:55.083
I let him Uncle Tom me

1:17:55.166 --> 1:17:58.291
just so he can tell himself
he's not a complete loser.

1:18:00.583 --> 1:18:02.625
How very considerate.

1:18:03.125 --> 1:18:05.208
It's his defense, Michael.

1:18:05.291 --> 1:18:08.083
You have your defense,
but it's indescribable.

1:18:11.708 --> 1:18:17.000
Y'all want to hear a little polite
parlor jest from the liberal Deep South?

1:18:17.083 --> 1:18:20.375
Do you know
why niggers have such big lips?

1:18:20.458 --> 1:18:23.166
Because they're always going…

1:18:23.250 --> 1:18:25.791
Christ, Michael!
Give me that. Let go, Michael.

1:18:27.208 --> 1:18:30.833
I can do without your goddamn spit
on my telephone, you nellie coward!

1:18:30.916 --> 1:18:33.291
I may be nellie, but I'm no coward!

1:18:35.875 --> 1:18:37.041
Yo, Bernard…

1:18:38.375 --> 1:18:39.666
forgive me. I'm sorry.

1:18:39.750 --> 1:18:42.250
I won't ever say
those things to you again.

1:18:56.625 --> 1:18:57.708
Huh.

1:19:03.750 --> 1:19:05.416
-BY.
-It's busy?

1:19:05.500 --> 1:19:07.666
Loraine is probably talking to her mother.

1:19:09.000 --> 1:19:11.208
Oh, yes, Delbert married Loraine.

1:19:11.291 --> 1:19:14.000
I'm sorry, you'll have
to forfeit your turn. We can't wait.

1:19:14.916 --> 1:19:17.041
Well, you're not wasting any time.

1:19:17.708 --> 1:19:19.625
-Who are you calling?
- Charlie.

1:19:20.500 --> 1:19:23.791
I refuse to forfeit my turn.
It is my turn, and I'm taking it.

1:19:23.875 --> 1:19:25.750
That's the spirit, Emory.

1:19:25.833 --> 1:19:29.500
You hit that iceberg! Don't miss it.
Hit it! God damn it!

1:19:29.583 --> 1:19:31.500
I want a smash of a finale.

1:19:31.583 --> 1:19:34.666
- God, I'm drunk.
-You're a falling-down-drunk-nellie-queen.

1:19:34.750 --> 1:19:36.958
Now that's the pot
calling the kettle beige.

1:19:37.041 --> 1:19:41.000
I am not drunk.
You cannot tell that I am drunk.

1:19:41.083 --> 1:19:42.875
-I'm drunk.
- So am I.

1:19:42.958 --> 1:19:44.708
-I am a major drunk.
-Shut up and dial.

1:19:44.791 --> 1:19:49.125
I'm a major drunk
of this or any other season.

1:19:56.041 --> 1:19:57.708
It's ringing. It's no longer BY.

1:20:00.833 --> 1:20:02.500
-Hello?
- One point.

1:20:05.000 --> 1:20:06.000
Who's speaking?

1:20:07.458 --> 1:20:08.291
Who?

1:20:10.041 --> 1:20:11.375
Dr. Delbert Botts?

1:20:11.458 --> 1:20:12.625
Two points.

1:20:17.458 --> 1:20:19.208
Del, is this really you?

1:20:22.625 --> 1:20:24.791
Nobody.

1:20:28.625 --> 1:20:31.333
Yeah, you don't know me.
You wouldn't remember me.

1:20:32.166 --> 1:20:33.000
Um…

1:20:37.375 --> 1:20:38.666
I'm just a friend.

1:20:40.791 --> 1:20:42.958
A falling-down, drunken friend.

1:20:47.583 --> 1:20:48.708
Hello?

1:20:51.458 --> 1:20:52.458
Hello?

1:20:56.625 --> 1:20:57.625
Hello?

1:21:10.500 --> 1:21:13.583
- He hung up.
-Three points total. You're winning.

1:21:13.666 --> 1:21:15.125
He said I must have the wrong party.

1:21:15.208 --> 1:21:17.916
Well, he's right. We have the wrong party.

1:21:19.708 --> 1:21:22.083
It's your party, Hallie.
Having a good time?

1:21:22.166 --> 1:21:23.666
Simply fabulous.

1:21:23.750 --> 1:21:26.291
How about you?
Are you having a good time, Emory?

1:21:26.375 --> 1:21:29.083
Are you having as good a time
as you thought you would?

1:21:35.625 --> 1:21:38.000
-My turn now.
-No, it's my turn to call Charlie.

1:21:38.083 --> 1:21:40.916
No… Let me.

1:21:42.791 --> 1:21:44.333
Are you gonna call Charlie?

1:21:45.250 --> 1:21:46.875
Don't, Hank.

1:21:46.958 --> 1:21:47.958
I want to.

1:21:50.666 --> 1:21:51.541
Larry.

1:21:54.666 --> 1:21:56.458
Be my eager guest.

1:21:58.625 --> 1:22:00.166
Is he gonna call Charlie for you?

1:22:00.750 --> 1:22:03.291
Charlie is all the people
I cheat on Hank with.

1:22:03.375 --> 1:22:05.166
With whom I cheat on Hank.

1:22:05.250 --> 1:22:07.625
The butcher, the baker,
the candlestick maker.

1:22:07.708 --> 1:22:09.666
Right! I love 'em all,

1:22:09.750 --> 1:22:13.083
but what Hank refuses to understand
is I gotta have 'em all.

1:22:13.166 --> 1:22:15.541
I'm not the marrying kind.
I never will be.

1:22:15.625 --> 1:22:16.708
Who're you calling?

1:22:16.791 --> 1:22:18.250
Did it ever occur to you

1:22:18.333 --> 1:22:20.666
that Hank might be doing
the same thing behind your back

1:22:20.750 --> 1:22:21.750
that you do behind his?

1:22:21.833 --> 1:22:25.833
I wish to Christ he would.
Would make life a hell of a lot easier.

1:22:25.916 --> 1:22:26.791
Who are you calling?

1:22:26.875 --> 1:22:30.916
Well, whoever it is, they're not
sitting on top of the telephone.

1:22:31.000 --> 1:22:33.166
-Hello?
-Must have been in the tub.

1:22:33.250 --> 1:22:34.166
One point.

1:22:34.250 --> 1:22:37.416
- I'd like to leave a message.
-Oh, not in. One point.

1:22:37.500 --> 1:22:39.166
Would you say that Hank called?

1:22:40.583 --> 1:22:41.500
Yes, it is.

1:22:43.041 --> 1:22:45.583
-Oh, good evening. How are you?
-Who the hell is that?

1:22:45.666 --> 1:22:48.875
Yes, that's right.
The message is for my roommate, Larry.

1:22:48.958 --> 1:22:50.416
-Just say that I called…

1:22:50.500 --> 1:22:52.458
It's our answering service.

1:22:52.541 --> 1:22:54.916
…and said I love you.

1:22:56.583 --> 1:22:58.000
Hank, are you crazy?

1:22:59.000 --> 1:23:01.583
You heard me correctly.
The message is for Larry.

1:23:01.666 --> 1:23:04.250
It's from me, Hank,
and it is just as I said.

1:23:07.541 --> 1:23:08.583
I love you.

1:23:12.375 --> 1:23:13.291
Yeah, thanks.

1:23:14.583 --> 1:23:16.291
Seven points total.

1:23:16.375 --> 1:23:20.083
Hank, you're ahead, baby!
You're way, way ahead of everybody.

1:23:20.166 --> 1:23:22.416
Why, Hank? Why did you do that?

1:23:23.833 --> 1:23:26.541
Because I do love him,
and I don't care who knows it.

1:23:26.625 --> 1:23:28.916
- Don't say that.
-Why not? It's the truth.

1:23:30.458 --> 1:23:32.333
I left my wife and family for Larry.

1:23:32.416 --> 1:23:34.875
-I'm not interested in hearing about it.
-Sure you are.

1:23:34.958 --> 1:23:36.666
Go ahead, Hankola. Tell him all about it.

1:23:36.750 --> 1:23:39.791
-I don't want to hear it! It's disgusting.
-Some men do it for another woman.

1:23:39.875 --> 1:23:42.458
Well, I can understand that.
That's normal.

1:23:45.041 --> 1:23:47.000
It doesn't always work out that way, Alan.

1:23:48.166 --> 1:23:50.833
No matter how you might want it to,
and God knows,

1:23:50.916 --> 1:23:53.000
nobody ever wanted it more than I did.

1:23:55.500 --> 1:23:58.000
I really and truly felt
I was in love with my wife

1:23:58.083 --> 1:23:59.416
when I married her, but…

1:24:01.458 --> 1:24:03.333
there was always that something else.

1:24:03.875 --> 1:24:05.000
Always?

1:24:09.250 --> 1:24:12.083
I don't know. I suppose so.

1:24:12.916 --> 1:24:15.666
I've known what I was
since I was four years old.

1:24:15.750 --> 1:24:18.291
Oh, everybody's always known it
about you, Emory.

1:24:18.375 --> 1:24:20.833
I've always known it about myself, too.

1:24:22.166 --> 1:24:24.666
I don't know
when I first admitted it to myself that…

1:24:27.833 --> 1:24:30.666
I always labeled it something else
or denied it completely.

1:24:30.750 --> 1:24:33.875
Oh. "Christ, was I drunk last night."

1:24:33.958 --> 1:24:36.500
There came a time
where I couldn't lie to myself anymore.

1:24:37.666 --> 1:24:41.291
I thought about it
but never did anything about it.

1:24:44.708 --> 1:24:47.458
The first time
was during my wife's last pregnancy.

1:24:50.375 --> 1:24:52.666
We lived near New Haven in the country.

1:24:52.750 --> 1:24:54.750
There was
this teachers' meeting in New York.

1:24:56.333 --> 1:24:59.875
My wife didn't feel up to the trip.
I came into town on my own and…

1:25:01.625 --> 1:25:04.041
That day on the train,
I began to think about it.

1:25:05.791 --> 1:25:07.041
And think about it.

1:25:08.583 --> 1:25:09.916
And think about it.

1:25:12.541 --> 1:25:14.375
<i>I thought of nothing else the whole trip.</i>

1:25:17.208 --> 1:25:19.208
<i>And then 15 minutes after I had arrived,</i>

1:25:19.291 --> 1:25:22.500
<i>I'd picked up a guy in the men's room</i>
<i>of Grand Central Station.</i>

1:25:22.583 --> 1:25:23.916
Jesus.

1:25:24.500 --> 1:25:26.458
I'd never done
anything like that before.

